The share of geothermal resources that can be exploited economically at present is referred to as geothermal reserves. These can be determined by comparing the levelized costs of energy (LCOE) with the average revenues earned from the sale of electricity and heat. LCOE describes the ratio of the power plant’s net present value (NPV), including the total investment cinvest, the operation and maintenance costs cO&M, and the potential revenues r, to the NPV of the net electricity generated over the project lifetime (Short et al., 1995), thus:9LCOE=∑t(cinvest,t+cO&M,t+rt)·1+d-t∑tEnet·1+d-t\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{LCOE}} = \frac{{\mathop \sum \nolimits_{t} (c_{{{{\rm invest}}, t}} + c_{{{\text{O}}\& {\text{M}},t}} + r_{t} ) \cdot \left( {1 + d} \right)^{ - t} }}{{\mathop \sum \nolimits_{t} E_{{{{\rm net}}}} \cdot \left( {1 + d} \right)^{ - t} }}$$\end{document}

Drilling and well completion are the largest cost figures and can reach up to 70% of the total investment for EGS projects. Empirical well cost equations, e.g., published by Legarth (2003), Bloomfield and Laney (2005), Tester et al. (2006), Lukawski et al. (2014) and Schlagermann (2014), generally show an exponential or quadratic increase in cost with depth. For this study, the empirical equation of Schlagermann (2014) was used (Table 1), which focuses on the German market. A simple doublet system with one production well and one injection well was assumed, as this is until now still the standard for EGS projects in the URG. Geothermal wells are usually drilled from one platform and thus need to be deviated to develop a sufficiently large reservoir volume. The resulting measured depth zmd (m) of a well was approximated as:10zmd=ztvd2+s2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
